## std::variant — Type-Safe Discriminated Union

`std::variant` replaces raw C unions with compile-time type safety:

```cpp
#include <variant>
#include <string>
#include <iostream>

using Value = std::variant<int, double, std::string>;

void process(const Value& v) {
    // std::visit with a visitor (pattern matching)
    std::visit([](auto&& arg) {
        using T = std::decay_t<decltype(arg)>;
        if constexpr (std::is_same_v<T, int>)
            std::cout << "int: " << arg << '\n';
        else if constexpr (std::is_same_v<T, double>)
            std::cout << "double: " << arg << '\n';
        else
            std::cout << "string: " << arg << '\n';
    }, v);
}
```

### Querying the active alternative

```cpp
Value v = 42;
if (std::holds_alternative<int>(v)) {
    int val = std::get<int>(v);  // throws bad_variant_access if wrong
}

// Safe access (no exception):
if (auto* p = std::get_if<double>(&v)) {
    std::cout << *p;
}
```

### Overloaded visitor pattern

```cpp
template<class... Ts> struct overloaded : Ts... { using Ts::operator()...; };
template<class... Ts> overloaded(Ts...) -> overloaded<Ts...>;

std::visit(overloaded{
    [](int i)    { std::cout << "int: " << i; },
    [](double d) { std::cout << "dbl: " << d; },
    [](const std::string& s) { std::cout << "str: " << s; }
}, v);
```

Key properties: `std::variant` is **never empty** (unless `valueless_by_exception`), assignment is type-safe, and `std::visit` enables exhaustive pattern matching at compile time.

## std::variant Exception Safety

A `std::variant` can enter the **valueless-by-exception** state when type-changing assignment or emplacement throws:

```cpp
struct Throws {
    Throws() = default;
    Throws(const Throws&) { throw std::runtime_error("copy failed"); }
};

std::variant<int, Throws> v = 42;  // holds int
try {
    v = Throws{};  // move/copy construction of Throws throws
} catch (...) {
    // v is now valueless_by_exception!
    assert(v.valueless_by_exception());
    assert(v.index() == std::variant_npos);
}
```

### When it happens

- **Type-changing assignment** where the new type's constructor throws
- **emplace()** where the constructor throws
- Does NOT happen with same-type assignment (just normal exception propagation)

### Guarding against it

1. **Use nothrow-movable types**: If all alternatives are nothrow move-constructible, variant uses move + swap internally — no valueless state possible
2. **Use emplace with care**: Wrap in try/catch and re-emplace a fallback
3. **Double-buffer pattern**: `std::variant<std::monostate, T1, T2>` — monostate as safe fallback

```cpp
// Safe: int is nothrow, so type-change from string->int never goes valueless
std::variant<int, std::string> v = "hello";
v = 42;  // guaranteed safe: int(42) is noexcept
```

Always check `valueless_by_exception()` after catching exceptions from variant operations.

## std::optional — Nullable Value Wrapper

`std::optional<T>` holds either a `T` or nothing, replacing sentinel values and nullable pointers for value semantics:

```cpp
#include <optional>
#include <string>

std::optional<int> find_index(const std::string& haystack, char needle) {
    auto pos = haystack.find(needle);
    if (pos != std::string::npos)
        return static_cast<int>(pos);
    return std::nullopt;  // "no value"
}
```

### Value access

```cpp
auto result = find_index("hello", 'l');
if (result) {                    // bool conversion
    int idx = *result;           // unchecked dereference
    int idx2 = result.value();   // throws bad_optional_access if empty
}
int idx = result.value_or(-1);   // default if empty
```

### C++23 monadic operations

```cpp
// transform: map over the contained value
auto doubled = result.transform([](int i) { return i * 2; });

// and_then: chain operations that return optional
auto chained = result.and_then([](int i) -> std::optional<std::string> {
    return i > 0 ? std::optional{std::to_string(i)} : std::nullopt;
});

// or_else: provide fallback
auto fallback = result.or_else([] { return std::optional{0}; });
```

### When to use what

| Scenario | Use |
|----------|-----|
| Function may not return a value | `std::optional` |
| Nullable ownership | `std::unique_ptr` |
| Non-owning nullable reference | `T*` or `std::optional<std::reference_wrapper<T>>` |
| Performance-critical hot path (avoid branch) | Sentinel value |

`std::optional` stores the value inline (no heap allocation), has value semantics, and makes the "might be empty" contract explicit in the type system.

## Expression Tree via std::variant

Recursive types need indirection. Combine `std::variant` with `std::unique_ptr`:

```cpp
#include <variant>
#include <memory>
#include <string>
#include <iostream>

struct Expr;  // forward declaration

struct Literal { double value; };
struct BinOp {
    char op;
    std::unique_ptr<Expr> left;
    std::unique_ptr<Expr> right;
};
struct UnaryOp {
    char op;
    std::unique_ptr<Expr> operand;
};

struct Expr {
    std::variant<Literal, BinOp, UnaryOp> node;
};
```

### Building expressions

```cpp
auto make_lit(double v) {
    return std::make_unique<Expr>(Expr{Literal{v}});
}
auto make_bin(char op, std::unique_ptr<Expr> l, std::unique_ptr<Expr> r) {
    return std::make_unique<Expr>(Expr{BinOp{op, std::move(l), std::move(r)}});
}

// Build: (3 + 4) * 2
auto tree = make_bin('*', make_bin('+', make_lit(3), make_lit(4)), make_lit(2));
```

### Evaluating with std::visit

```cpp
double eval(const Expr& expr) {
    return std::visit(overloaded{
        [](const Literal& lit) { return lit.value; },
        [](const BinOp& bin) -> double {
            double l = eval(*bin.left), r = eval(*bin.right);
            switch (bin.op) {
                case '+': return l + r;
                case '*': return l * r;
                default: throw std::runtime_error("unknown op");
            }
        },
        [](const UnaryOp& un) -> double {
            double v = eval(*un.operand);
            return un.op == '-' ? -v : v;
        }
    }, expr.node);
}
```

This pattern gives you type-safe ASTs with automatic memory management via `unique_ptr`, exhaustive matching via `std::visit`, and zero raw pointers.

## std::variant vs Virtual Dispatch

### std::variant (closed set of types)

```cpp
using Shape = std::variant<Circle, Rectangle, Triangle>;

double area(const Shape& s) {
    return std::visit(overloaded{
        [](const Circle& c)    { return 3.14159 * c.r * c.r; },
        [](const Rectangle& r) { return r.w * r.h; },
        [](const Triangle& t)  { return 0.5 * t.base * t.height; }
    }, s);
}
```

### Inheritance (open set of types)

```cpp
struct Shape {
    virtual ~Shape() = default;
    virtual double area() const = 0;
};
struct Circle : Shape {
    double r;
    double area() const override { return 3.14159 * r * r; }
};
```

### Comparison

| Aspect | `std::variant` | Inheritance |
|--------|---------------|-------------|
| **Type set** | Closed (fixed at compile time) | Open (add subclasses freely) |
| **Adding types** | Modify variant + all visitors | Add new subclass, no existing code changes |
| **Adding operations** | Add new `std::visit` call | Add new virtual method to every subclass |
| **Memory** | Stack-allocated, size = max alternative | Heap-allocated, pointer indirection |
| **Performance** | No vtable, no indirection, cache-friendly | Virtual dispatch overhead |
| **Type safety** | Exhaustive matching at compile time | Can forget to override |

### When to use which

- **variant**: Known fixed set of types, performance-critical, value semantics, need exhaustive handling
- **inheritance**: Plugin architectures, type set grows over time, need runtime extensibility
- **Hybrid**: `std::variant` of `std::unique_ptr<Base>` for open sets with value-like containers

## std::optional and Move Semantics

### Moving from optional

```cpp
std::optional<std::string> opt = "hello world";
std::string s = std::move(*opt);  // moves the contained string
// opt still has a value! But *opt is in moved-from state (valid but unspecified)
assert(opt.has_value());  // true — optional is still engaged
// *opt is empty string (moved-from std::string)
```

Key: `std::move(*opt)` moves the **contained value**, not the optional itself. The optional remains engaged.

```cpp
std::optional<std::string> opt2 = std::move(opt);
// Now opt is still engaged but holds moved-from string
// opt2 holds "hello world" (if moved before line above)
```

### Moving the optional itself

```cpp
std::optional<std::vector<int>> a = std::vector{1,2,3};
auto b = std::move(a);  // b has the vector, a is engaged but empty vector
```

### No optional<T&> in the standard

`std::optional<T&>` is not supported. Alternatives:

```cpp
// 1. Pointer (simplest)
int* maybe_ref = condition ? &x : nullptr;

// 2. reference_wrapper
std::optional<std::reference_wrapper<int>> opt_ref = std::ref(x);
int& val = opt_ref->get();

// 3. Proposed for C++26: std::optional<T&> with rebinding semantics
```

### Performance

- `std::optional<T>` stores `T` inline + 1 bool flag (no heap allocation)
- Size = `sizeof(T) + alignment padding + 1 byte` (sometimes optimized)
- Trivially destructible `T` → trivially destructible `optional<T>`
- Move is as cheap as moving `T` + copying a bool

## Advanced std::variant Patterns

### 1. State Machine

```cpp
struct Idle {};
struct Connecting { std::string host; int retries = 0; };
struct Connected { int socket_fd; };
struct Error { std::string message; };

using State = std::variant<Idle, Connecting, Connected, Error>;

struct Event_Connect { std::string host; };
struct Event_Success { int fd; };
struct Event_Fail { std::string reason; };
struct Event_Disconnect {};

using Event = std::variant<Event_Connect, Event_Success, Event_Fail, Event_Disconnect>;

State transition(State state, const Event& event) {
    return std::visit(overloaded{
        [](Idle, const Event_Connect& e) -> State { return Connecting{e.host}; },
        [](Connecting& c, const Event_Success& e) -> State { return Connected{e.fd}; },
        [](Connecting& c, const Event_Fail& e) -> State {
            return c.retries < 3 ? State{Connecting{c.host, c.retries + 1}}
                                 : State{Error{e.reason}};
        },
        [](Connected, const Event_Disconnect&) -> State { return Idle{}; },
        [](auto&&, auto&&) -> State { return std::move(state); }  // ignore invalid transitions
    }, std::move(state), event);
}
```

### 2. Multi-variant visitation

```cpp
std::variant<int, double> a = 3;
std::variant<std::string, bool> b = "hello";

// Visit TWO variants simultaneously
auto result = std::visit(overloaded{
    [](int i, const std::string& s) { return s + std::to_string(i); },
    [](int i, bool b) { return std::to_string(i * b); },
    [](double d, const std::string& s) { return s + std::to_string(d); },
    [](double d, bool b) { return std::to_string(d * b); }
}, a, b);
```

### 3. Variant as error handling

```cpp
template<typename T>
using Result = std::variant<T, std::string>;  // value or error message

Result<int> parse_int(std::string_view s) {
    try { return std::stoi(std::string(s)); }
    catch (...) { return std::string("parse failed: ") + std::string(s); }
}
```

Variant-based state machines are exhaustively checked at compile time — adding a new state forces updating all transition handlers.

## std::optional Best Practices

### When to use

- Function that may not produce a result
- Optional configuration parameters
- Lazy initialization of expensive objects
- Replacing sentinel values (`-1`, `""`, `nullptr`)

### When NOT to use

```cpp
// BAD: optional<bool> is confusing (three states)
std::optional<bool> flag;  // true, false, or not-set?
// BETTER: use an enum
enum class TriState { True, False, NotSet };

// BAD: optional for error handling
std::optional<int> divide(int a, int b);  // why did it fail?
// BETTER: std::expected<int, Error> (C++23) or variant<int, Error>

// BAD: optional<unique_ptr<T>> — double indirection, double nullability
std::optional<std::unique_ptr<Foo>> x;  // can be nullopt OR hold nullptr
// BETTER: just use unique_ptr<Foo>

// BAD: optional in performance-critical containers
std::vector<std::optional<int>> v;  // 8 bytes per element instead of 4
// BETTER: separate validity bitmap or sentinel
```

### Common mistakes

```cpp
// 1. Forgetting optional stays engaged after move
auto s = std::move(*opt);  // opt is still engaged!
opt.reset();  // explicit disengage if needed

// 2. Comparing optional to value (works but surprising)
std::optional<int> a = 5;
if (a == 5) {}   // OK: compares contained value
if (a == std::nullopt) {}  // OK: checks emptiness

// 3. Using value() without checking (throws bad_optional_access)
try { opt.value(); }  // prefer: if (opt) { *opt; }
```

### Performance notes

- Trivially copyable `T` → `optional<T>` is also trivially copyable
- No heap allocation ever — value is stored inline
- Size overhead is typically 1 byte + alignment padding
- `std::optional<double>` is 16 bytes (8 + 1 + 7 padding) on most platforms

## Type-Safe Command Dispatcher with std::variant

```cpp
#include <variant>
#include <string>
#include <iostream>

// Define command types
struct CreateUser { std::string name; std::string email; };
struct DeleteUser { int user_id; };
struct UpdateEmail { int user_id; std::string new_email; };
struct ListUsers { int page; int per_page; };

using Command = std::variant<CreateUser, DeleteUser, UpdateEmail, ListUsers>;

// Overloaded helper for clean visitor syntax
template<class... Ts> struct overloaded : Ts... { using Ts::operator()...; };
template<class... Ts> overloaded(Ts...) -> overloaded<Ts...>;

// Dispatch — compiler enforces handling ALL command types
std::string dispatch(const Command& cmd) {
    return std::visit(overloaded{
        [](const CreateUser& c) {
            return "Created user: " + c.name;
        },
        [](const DeleteUser& c) {
            return "Deleted user #" + std::to_string(c.user_id);
        },
        [](const UpdateEmail& c) {
            return "Updated email for #" + std::to_string(c.user_id);
        },
        [](const ListUsers& c) {
            return "Page " + std::to_string(c.page);
        }
        // If you add a new command type to the variant but forget
        // to handle it here, the compiler emits an error.
    }, cmd);
}
```

### Compile-time exhaustiveness

If you add `struct BanUser { int user_id; };` to the variant but forget to add a visitor case, the compiler produces an error like:

```
error: no matching function for call to 'overloaded<...>::operator()(const BanUser&)'
```

This is the key advantage over `if-else` chains or `dynamic_cast` — impossible to silently miss a case. Combined with `std::variant`'s lack of heap allocation, this pattern gives you zero-overhead, type-safe dispatch.

## Algebraic Data Types with std::variant

C++ `std::variant` implements **sum types** (tagged unions) — the same concept as Rust `enum` or Haskell `data`:

### Haskell
```haskell
data Maybe a = Nothing | Just a
data Either a b = Left a | Right b
data Expr = Lit Int | Add Expr Expr | Neg Expr
```

### Rust
```rust
enum Maybe<T> { Nothing, Just(T) }
enum Expr { Lit(i32), Add(Box<Expr>, Box<Expr>), Neg(Box<Expr>) }
```

### C++
```cpp
// Maybe<T>
template<typename T>
using Maybe = std::variant<std::monostate, T>;  // monostate = Nothing

// Either<L, R>
template<typename L, typename R>
using Either = std::variant<L, R>;

// Result<T, E> (like Rust Result)
template<typename T, typename E = std::string>
using Result = std::variant<T, E>;
```

### Pattern matching comparison

```cpp
// C++ (verbose but type-safe)
std::visit(overloaded{
    [](std::monostate) { std::cout << "Nothing"; },
    [](int value)      { std::cout << "Just " << value; }
}, maybe_val);

// Rust (concise)
// match maybe_val { Nothing => ..., Just(v) => ... }

// Haskell (most concise)
// case maybeVal of Nothing -> ...; Just v -> ...
```

### Key differences

| Feature | C++ variant | Rust enum | Haskell data |
|---------|------------|-----------|-------------|
| Syntax | Verbose | Clean | Cleanest |
| Exhaustiveness | Compile-time | Compile-time | Compile-time |
| Recursion | Needs unique_ptr | Needs Box | Built-in |
| Methods | External (visit) | impl block | Typeclass |
| Memory | Stack, no alloc | Stack, no alloc | GC heap |

All three provide the same guarantees: exhaustive matching, type safety, no invalid states. C++ requires more boilerplate but has identical runtime characteristics to Rust.
